'''Wilhelm Delano Meriwether''' (born April 23, 1943<ref name="masters1">{{cite web|url=http://www.mastersathletics.net/fileadmin/html/Rankings/All_Time/100metresmen.htm|title=All Time World Rankings - 100 metres Dash |publisher=Mastersathletics.net|accessdate=March 6, 2009}}</ref><ref name="si1"/>) is an [[United States|American]] [[physician]] and a former [[track and field]] athlete. He is best known for having been the head of the [[United States Government]] 1976 [[swine flu]] [[immunization]] program and as the 1971 [[National champions 100 metres (men)#United States|US outdoor track and field champion]] in the [[100 yard dash]].

==Early life==
Meriwether was born in [[Nashville, Tennessee]], [[United States]] to parents who were teachers. His father, Wilhelm R. Meriwether, in time became a principal of [[Burke High School (South Carolina)|Burke High School]] in [[Charleston, South Carolina]] where the younger Meriwether was educated. At Burke he played [[saxophone]] on the school band and was a member of the Science Club.<ref name="si1"/><ref name="pyatt1">{{cite book|last=Pyatt|first=Sherman E.|title=Burke High School: 1894-2006|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2007|pages=27|isbn=0-7385-4412-4|accessdate=March 12, 2009}}</ref><ref name="CCP1">{{cite news|url=http://www.charlestoncitypaper.com/gyrobase/Content?oid=oid%3A39294|title=New book on Burke High chronicles the school's history|last=Blakeney|first=Barney|date=January 23, 2008|publisher=Charleston City Paper|accessdate=March 9, 2009}}</ref><ref name="pyatt3">{{cite book|last=Pyatt|first=Sherman E.|title=Burke High School: 1894-2006|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2007|pages=39|isbn=0-7385-4412-4|accessdate=12 March 2009}}</ref> His sporting involvement at high school was limited as he was considered too small for [[basketball]] and [[American football|football]].<ref name="si3"/>  Meriwether graduated from Burke in 1960.<ref name="pyatt2">{{cite book|last=Pyatt|first=Sherman E.|title=Burke High School: 1894-2006|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|year=2007|pages=9|isbn=0-7385-4412-4|accessdate=March 12, 2009}}</ref>

While still at high school Meriwether worked in a veterinary hospital having already won an award from the [[American Veterinary Medical Association]] as a 16 year old for research on internal parasites found in dogs.<ref name="si1"/><ref name="science">{{cite book|year=1959|work=Science News-letter |publisher=Science Service|pages=359|accessdate=March 9, 2009}}</ref> After graduating from high school he received a scholarship to study at [[Michigan State University]]; taking pre-veterinary studies for two years before switching to [[pre-medical]].<ref name="si1"/> After three years he graduated from Michigan and became the first [[African American]] to be accepted into [[Duke University School of Medicine]],<ref name="time1">{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,903012-1,00.html|title=The Dr. Meriwether Saga|date=June 12, 1971|publisher=[[Time magazine]]|accessdate=March 6, 2009}}</ref> graduating with honors in 1967 and then obtained a [[Master's degree]] in Public Health from [[Johns Hopkins University]].<ref name="dailynews1">{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/2007/01/14/2007-01-14_medical_miracle_meriwether_beats_all_odd.html|title=MEDICAL MIRACLE. Meriwether beats all odds on track & in life |date=January 14, 2007|language=[[New York Daily News]]|accessdate=March 6, 2009}}</ref>

==Medicine==
After graduating from Duke, Meriwether took his internship at the [[Penn State Milton S. Hershey Medical Center]], before starting a residency at [[The Ohio State University College of Medicine|Ohio State University Medical Center]].<ref name="si1"/> He later specialized in [[hematology]], the study of blood, and had a number of papers published.<ref name="pubmed1">{{cite web|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/entrez?Db=pubmed&Cmd=Search&Term=%22Meriwether%20WD%22%5BAuthor%5D&itool=EntrezSystem2.PEntrez.Pubmed.Pubmed_ResultsPanel.Pubmed_RVAbstract|title=Meriwether WD - Author|publisher=[[PubMed]]|accessdate=March 12, 2009}}</ref><ref name="ebony1">{{cite journal|date=February 1972|title=The World's Fastest M.D.|journal=Ebony|publisher=Johnson Publishing Company|volume=27|issue=4|pages=59–64|issn=0012-901|accessdate=March 13, 2009}}</ref> In the early 1970s he worked researching [[Leukemia]] at the [[University of Maryland Greenebaum Cancer Center|Baltimore Cancer Research Center]],<ref name="courant1"/> and was a 1973-1974 [[White House Fellows|White House Fellow]].<ref name="people1"/>

In 1976 Meriwether, as Special Assistant to the Assistant Secretary of Health, was appointed Director of the [[United States Public Health Service]]'s National Influenza Immunization Program (NIIP). The NIIP sought to immunize over 200 million people against [[swine influenza]] within six months. This program faced much opposition as many doctors, pharmaceutical companies and insurance companies refused to take responsibility for mishaps. Meriwether became the public face of this campaign.<ref name="people1">{{cite news |last=Burstein |first=Patricia |title=A Champion Runner, Dr. Meriwether Finds the Swine Flu Program He Heads More Like An Obstacle Race |url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20067063,00.html |date=November 1, 1976 |publisher=[[People magazine]] |accessdate=March 6, 2009}}</ref><ref name="avianflu1">{{cite book|last=Orr|first=Tamra|title=Avian Flu|publisher=The Rosen Publishing Group|year=2007|pages=26|isbn=1-4042-0950-6}}</ref><ref name="neustadt1">{{cite book |last=Neustadt |first=Richard E.  |coauthors=Fineberg, Harvey V. |title=The Epidemic that Never was: Policy-making and the Swine Flu Scare |publisher=Vintage Books |year=1983 |pages=159, 172 |isbn=0-394-71147-5 |accessdate=March 13, 2009}}</ref><ref name="house1">{{cite book|title=Hearings, Reports and Prints of the House Committee on Interstate and Foreign Commerce |publisher=[[United States Congress]] |year=1976 |accessdate=March 13, 2009}}</ref>

In 1983 he moved to [[Gazankulu]] in [[South Africa]] where he worked as a [[missionary]] doctor and was one of six physicians treating a half million people.<ref name="si2"/><ref name="ata1">{{cite web|url=http://www.africa-ata.org/meticulous2.htm|title=Nomvimbi Meriwether|publisher=Africa Travel Association|accessdate=March 9, 2009}}</ref> He later worked and lived in the [[Soweto]] township.

Meriwether returned to the United States in 1990 working as an [[Emergency Room]] doctor.<ref name="si2"/><ref name="dukealum1">{{cite web |url=http://medalum.duke.edu/medAlum/DMANweb/Spring07/Meriwether.htm |title=A Relay to Remember — Meriwether Honored for Achievements in Track & Field |last=Gillis |first=Bernadette |date=Spring 2007 |publisher=Duke Medical Alumni Association |accessdate=March 6, 2009}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

