Meriwether began competitive running in 1970 while working at the Baltimore Cancer Research Center. In order to train Meriwether would scale a fence at the nearby [[Johns Hopkins University]] athletics track and would run at night in the dark.<ref name="courant1">{{cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/sports/bal-te.faces27,0,912962,full.story|title=Faces in the Crowd|last=Klingaman|first=Mike|date=November 26, 2005|publisher=[[Hartford Courant]]|accessdate=March 9, 2009}}</ref>  Due to his relative inexperience and unique attire, Meriwether drew the attention of the news media; appearing on the cover of [[Sports Illustrated]] magazine posing in his running gear,<ref name="si1"/> and also featured in [[Time magazine]].<ref name="time1"/> 

Meriwether made his mark as a runner at the [[Amateur Athletic Union]] [[USA Outdoor Track and Field Championships]] in [[Eugene, Oregon]] in June 1971 when he won the [[100 yard dash]].<ref name="si1">{{cite news|url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1084609/index.htm|title=Champion Of The Armchair Athletes|last=Boyle|first=Robert H.|date=February 22, 1971|publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]]|accessdate=March 6, 2009}}</ref> His appearance at the event was unusual for a number of reasons. He was unattached to any educational institution and he was wearing a [[Scrubs (clothing)|hospital shirt]], gold and white [[suspenders]] and [[Swimsuit|swimming trunks]]. The most remarkable element of the day was the time he recorded for the [[100 yard dash]]. In recording a nine second 100 yard he became the second runner to run the distance in nine seconds flat, the other being [[John Carlos]], however Meriwether's time did not count as a record as the run was [[100 metres#Climatic conditions|wind assisted]].<ref name="si3">{{cite news|url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1084486/index.htm|title=hey, I Can Beat Those Guys|last=Treadwell|first=Sandy|date=January 18, 1971|publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]]|accessdate=March 8, 2009}}</ref><ref name="time1"/><ref name="dailynews1"/><ref name="aden1">{{cite book|last=Aden|first=Roger|title=Popular Stories and Promised Lands |publisher=University of Alabama Press|year=1999|pages=204|accessdate=March 13, 2009}}</ref>

In 1972 Meriwether was the [[USA Indoor Track and Field Championships|United States Indoor Track and Field Champion]],<ref name="usatf1">{{cite web|url=http://www.usatf.org/statistics/champions/USAIndoorTF/men/m60m.asp|title=USA Indoor Track & Field Champions|publisher=[[USA Track & Field]]|accessdate=March 6, 2009}}</ref> but due to a knee injury he was unable to compete for selection for the United States [[1972 Summer Olympics|1972 Olympic Games]] team. After another injury prevented his chances of being selected for the [[1976 Summer Olympics|1976 Olympics]], he retired from regular competition to concentrate on medicine.<ref name="si2">{{cite news|url=http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1009660/index.htm|title=Sprinter Delano Meriwether|last=Noden|first=Merrill|date=March 24, 1997|publisher=[[Sports Illustrated]]|accessdate=March 6, 2009}}</ref>

For a number of years he ran in [[Masters athletics|masters]] events and his 200 meter run of 20.8 seconds in 1978 is still a current [[United States Records in Masters Athletics|national record]] in the 35-39 age group.<ref name="USATF2">{{cite web|url=http://www.usatf.org/statistics/records/view.asp?division=american&location=outdoor%20track%20%26%20field&age=masters&ageGroup=35-39&sport=TF|title=American Masters 35-39 Outdoor Track & Field Records|publisher=USA Track & Field|accessdate=March 6, 2009}}</ref>

==Personal Life==
Delano is married to Nomvimbi Meriwether, who runs a travel agency specializing in tours of Africa. Their daughter, [[Nana Meriwether]] (b. 1985) represented [[Maryland]] in the 2012 [[Miss USA]] Pageant and was named the New Miss USA 2012 on December 19, after current Miss USA Olivia Culpo became Miss Universe 2012.<ref name="WP1">{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/reliable-source/post/nana-meriwether-sidwell-friends-grad-is-first-runner-up-at-miss-usa/2012/06/04/gJQAaLPSDV_blog.html|title=Nana Meriwether, Sidwell Friends grad, is first runner-up at Miss USA|date=June 4, 2012|publisher=[[Washington Post]]|accessdate=June 4, 2012}}</ref>

==Popular culture==
The novel Bethany Park, by Glen Sharp, tells the story of a boy inspired to run after reading of Dr Meriwether's athletic endeavors in Sports Illustrated.<ref name="bethany1">{{cite book|last=Sharp|first=Glen|title=Bethany Park|publisher=booklocker.com|date=30 June 2006|isbn=1-60145-009-5}}</ref>

